  "prompt": "Why do electrons and protons attract each other?",
  "response": "Electrons and protons attract each other due to the fundamental electromagnetic force, which is one of the four fundamental forces of nature. This attractive interaction arises from their electric charges: electrons carry a negative charge, while protons carry a positive charge.\n\nAccording to Coulomb\u2019s Law, opposite charges attract each other, while like charges repel each other. In this case, the negative charge of the electron is attracted to the positive charge of the proton. This attraction is a consequence of the exchange of virtual photons, which are the force carriers for electromagnetic interactions.\n\nThis attraction between electrons and protons is crucial for the formation of atoms. Electrons are found in the electron cloud surrounding the nucleus, which is made up of protons (and neutrons). The balance between the attraction of electrons to protons and the principles of quantum mechanics leads to the stable structure of atoms.",
